window.docContents[250].resolve({"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Wiener___Ikehara-theorem-and-the-Prime-Number-Theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Wiener___Ikehara-theorem-and-the-Prime-Number-Theorem":{"contents":"The EulerProducts project of Michael Stoll develops Euler products in general and derives the Prime\nNumber Theorem and Dirichlet's theorem from a clean statement of the Wiener–Ikehara Tauberian theorem,\nwhich is taken as a hypothesis (the Tauberian theorem itself is proved analytically in\nPrimeNumberTheoremAnd). The nodes below are informal; each links to its exact source declaration at\ncommit 7376f1a and connects into the dependency graph through the mathlib-backed nodes above.\n\n(Euler product for a multiplicative -series.) Let  be weakly\nmultiplicative with , and suppose the -series \n() converges absolutely at . Then\n\nthe product of local factors over primes . When  is completely multiplicative the local factor\ncollapses to .\nFormalised in EulerProducts: LSeries.eulerProduct_of_multiplicative and LSeries.eulerProduct_of_completelyMultiplicative — sorry-free.\n\nThis is the general analytic incarnation of unique factorisation (): expanding\n and grouping by  reproduces each Dirichlet\ncoefficient  exactly once. The repository builds the term-level multiplicativity lemmas\n(term_multiplicative, term_completelyMultiplicative, term_at_one) and feeds them to the underlying\neulerProduct engine, with absolute convergence of  (LSeriesSummable) justifying the\nrearrangement of the double sum. The Euler products for  () and\nfor Dirichlet -functions () are the\ncompletely-multiplicative special cases, now part of mathlib.\n\n(Wiener–Ikehara Tauberian theorem, as a hypothesis.) Let  be a\nnon-negative arithmetic function and . Suppose there is a function  that is\ncontinuous on  and agrees on  with\n\nThen the partial sums satisfy\n\nThis statement is packaged in EulerProducts as a Prop-valued hypothesis WienerIkeharaTheorem,\nused as input to the Prime Number Theorem below; the Tauberian theorem itself is proved in\nPrimeNumberTheoremAnd ().\nFormalised in EulerProducts: WienerIkeharaTheorem — statement only (a hypothesis, discharged elsewhere).\n\nThe classical proof is a Fourier-analytic argument: one writes the partial sum as an inverse\nMellin-type integral along , and the hypothesis that\n extends continuously (not merely analytically) to the closed half-plane\n lets a smoothing and the Riemann–Lebesgue lemma kill the oscillatory part,\nleaving the residue  from the simple pole at  (). In EulerProducts\nthis is not reproved; it is named as the hypothesis WienerIkeharaTheorem and consumed by the PNT and\nDirichlet derivations.\n\n(Prime Number Theorem via Wiener–Ikehara.) Assume the Wiener–Ikehara theorem\n(). Then\n\ni.e.  for the Chebyshev function (). More generally, for\na unit , the von Mangoldt sum over the residue class\n is asymptotic to .\nFormalised in EulerProducts: PNT_vonMangoldt and Dirichlet_vonMangoldt — sorry-free (conditional on WienerIkeharaTheorem).\n\nOne applies the Wiener–Ikehara hypothesis () to the indicator-weighted von\nMangoldt function on a residue class, with . The role of the analytic input is\nthe auxiliary function vonMangoldt.LFunctionResidueClassAux, which equals  on\n (eqOn_LFunctionResidueClassAux) and is continuous on\n (continuousOn_LFunctionResidueClassAux) — the very continuity that the\nnon-vanishing of  and the Dirichlet -functions on that line provides\n(). The full PNT  is PNT_vonMangoldt, the special\ncase ,  of the residue-class statement Dirichlet_vonMangoldt, where the von Mangoldt\n-series is  ().\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Analytic Number Theory","header":"2.9. The Wiener–Ikehara theorem and the Prime Number Theorem","id":"/Analytic-Number-Theory/The-Wiener___Ikehara-theorem-and-the-Prime-Number-Theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Analytic-Number-Theory--The-Wiener___Ikehara-theorem-and-the-Prime-Number-Theorem"},"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-Weil-conjectures-and-the-Hasse___Weil-zeta-function/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-Weil-conjectures-and-the-Hasse___Weil-zeta-function":{"contents":"For a smooth projective scheme  over , writing \nfor the number of rational points over the degree- extension, the Hasse–Weil zeta function\nis the formal power series\n\nFormalised in WeilConjectures (private repo — link requires access):\nScheme.zetaFunction and Scheme.zetaSeries (WeilConjectures/ZetaFunction.lean#L31 and\n#L39, commit b8464ee) — sorry-free; defined as  of the logarithmic series\n.\n\n(Weil conjectures for smooth projective varieties over .) Given a Weil\ncohomology theory  with Frobenius action on a smooth projective variety\n of pure dimension , and the Lefschetz trace formula\n, the zeta function\n() satisfies: rationality, the cohomological factorisation\n with\n; the functional equation as Betti symmetry\n together with a per-polynomial duality\n;\nand, for curves (), the Riemann hypothesis ,\ni.e. the Hasse–Weil bound ().\nFormalised in WeilConjectures (private repo — link requires access): weil_conjectures\n(WeilConjectures/Statement.lean#L46, commit b8464ee) — in progress. The functional\nequation, per-polynomial duality, and curve Riemann hypothesis are derived from the Weil\ncohomology axioms; the rationality bridge carries the two remaining sorries\n(RationalityBridge.lean#L181, #L205: a chain-rule step for the formal -substitution\nand the ODE-uniqueness identification of the geometric and cohomological zeta series).\n\nThe argument is an abstract deduction from the axioms of a Weil cohomology theory  with\nFrobenius data  (abstract_weil_conjectures). Rationality: the Lefschetz trace formula\nturns  into ;\nboth  and  satisfy the same linear ODE\nwith matching initial value, and ODE uniqueness (ode_unique) identifies them — this is the\nrationality_bridge, whose two analytic steps remain deferred. Functional equation: the\nPoincaré pairing  is nondegenerate (poincare_left,\npoincare_right), so , i.e. \n(abstract_functional_equation), and the duality of charpolys is per_polynomial_duality.\nCurve Riemann hypothesis: for  the bound is packaged as the hypothesis CurveRH\n(the Hodge-index input on the surface ), and abstract_curve_rh reads off\n, the Hasse–Weil bound () for all .\n\nFor an elliptic curve  () over , the Hasse–Weil zeta\nfunction () is explicitly rational:\n\nwith  the trace of Frobenius\n(, ).\n\nThis is the  case of the cohomological factorisation (). The\ndenominator  is  for the degree- and degree- cohomology,\nwhose Frobenius eigenvalues are  and . The numerator  is\n, of trace  and determinant  (the\nWeil pairing). The Riemann hypothesis for curves, equivalently the roots of  having\nabsolute value , is the Hasse bound ().\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elliptic Curves and Arithmetic Geometry","header":"7.12. The Weil conjectures and the Hasse–Weil zeta function","id":"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/The-Weil-conjectures-and-the-Hasse___Weil-zeta-function/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--The-Weil-conjectures-and-the-Hasse___Weil-zeta-function"}});